Subsidy trap
The United States Cambridge—no policy stands as directly at odds between good economics and good politics as food and energy subsidies.
Subsidies that are unaffordable have become the core issue facing the three most important new leaders in the world. They are Egyptian President Sisi, Indonesian President "Jokowi" Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Modi.
The subsidies cuts that Sisi faces require to be better than anticipated.
In contrast, Modi faces a worse situation than anticipated, potentially undermining the long-anticipated World Trade Organization agreement.
While the situation facing Jokowi remains unclear.
In July, Sisi achieved something few leaders in North Africa and the Middle East have managed: he significantly cut long-standing energy subsidies, raising prices by 41 to 78 percent.
It is strange that there was almost no protest against it.
Egypt's food subsidy program costs more than $5 billion annually and urgently needs reform.
Bread prices have remained at extremely low levels, often used to feed animals.
In the past, efforts by North African countries to cut such subsidies often led to unrest, even toppling governments.
But Sisi's government also seems to be making progress in this area.
The bread subsidy has been reduced by 13 percent.
Sisi had no choice.
Even after the subsidy cuts, the current government's budget deficit target for the next fiscal year reached 10 percent of GDP (which would have been 14 percent without the subsidy reductions).
However, few people anticipated that Sisi, who came to power in a turbulent political environment, could act more swiftly than Modi. Modi became prime minister of India, where there was an overwhelming democratic majority, through a strong desire for comprehensive economic reform.
In Indonesia, Jokowi inherited a long-standing fuel subsidy program worth as much as $21 billion annually (equivalent to 20 percent of government spending), which had already placed a heavy burden on the country.
The outgoing Susilo took a brave first step a year ago by raising fuel prices.
Jokowi's advisors recommended cutting the remaining subsidies, and he candidly stated his plan to implement the cuts gradually over four years.
Economists confidently oppose commodity subsidies, as agricultural and energy markets are close to perfect competition, with a large number of consumers on the demand side and a large number of producers on the supply side.
In imperfectly competitive markets, the government — not large private monopolies — is the source.
Critics of the invisible hand point out that self-regulating private markets may fail in various ways.
For example, income inequality and environmental externalities are the two main justifications for government intervention.
What makes food and fossil fuel subsidies controversial is that they are often justified under the banners of environment or equality, but in reality, they fail to achieve these goals and often do more harm than good.
Less than 20% of Egypt's food subsidies went to the poor.
Most countries' gasoline subsidies benefit the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, less than 0.1% of liquefied petroleum gas subsidies went to the poorest population, while 52.6% flowed into the pockets of the wealthiest.
For the entire world, less than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies went to the poorest 20% of the population.
Food and energy subsidies can also distort public policy, as evidenced by Modi's government, which aims to protect agricultural subsidies in India.
In fact, Modi's government vetoed the World Trade Organization compromise, causing the most significant progress in multilateral trade negotiations over the past decade to be lost.
Agricultural subsidies can sometimes benefit producers at the expense of consumers, especially in poor countries; whereas at other times they benefit consumers at the expense of producers, especially in rich countries.
India's policy aims to achieve both.
As a result, India accomplished a feat: it rationed wheat to consumers at artificially low prices while simultaneously experiencing oversupply, as farmers could obtain high prices.
Farmers also receive subsidies for agricultural inputs—electricity, water, and fertilizers—while the environment is damaged.
The government purchased large amounts of corrupt rice and wheat, and the small portion allocated to consumers was both corrupt and failed to serve the goal of helping the poor.
The government may continue to maintain subsidies and stockpiles.
But it knows that this would violate World Trade Organization rules.
Since it was impossible to permanently change these rules, Modi simply vetoed the Trade Facilitation Agreement that the World Trade Organization had been eagerly awaiting.
Once subsidies are implemented, it is difficult to withdraw them.
When global commodity prices rise (as they did in the past decade), citizens accustomed to market-determined domestic prices are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot shield them from such shocks.
But citizens accustomed to government-set prices for food and energy will demand that the government take responsibility.
This provides a strong rationale for not implementing subsidies from the beginning.
But this does not mean that maintaining subsidies once they are implemented is necessarily the best choice for shrewd politicians.
If the alternative to price increases is shortages or rationing, angry opponents may also erupt.
Similarly, if the continuously widening gap ultimately leads to greater retail price increases, slow-moving leaders will also not benefit.
In an ideal scenario, other more efficient measures to support low-income populations should be adopted alongside the reduction of food and energy subsidies.
Developing countries have gained significant experience in effective transfer mechanisms, such as Mexico's conditional cash transfer program Progresa-Oportunidades and Brazil's Bolsa Família program, as well as India's Unique Identification system, which represents technological innovations.
But some countries are forced to adjust only when a budget crisis occurs, and they may not have the funds available for transfer payments to alleviate the suffering.
Shrewd politicians might be better off implementing unpopular adjustments from the start.
Jokowi and Sisi both adopted this approach.
While Modi, who won the election with the slogan of market reforms, has fallen behind.
